Welsh National Assembly Members Fear They Will Be Called Muppets
This is the result of a proposal to change their title to Member of the Welsh Parliament (MWP).
The idea came about in connection with plans to rename the assembly to the Welsh Parliament.
Members of the assembly from all sides of the political scene are concerned that they may become the subject of mockery.
One Labour MP expressed his group's concerns, saying the new name rhymes with the Welsh words "twp" and "pwp".
For non-Wales readers: in Welsh, the word "twp" means stupid, and the word "pwp" means excrement.
Plaid Cymru, one of the party’s politicians, said his party was “dissatisfied” with the proposal and presented other solutions.
A member of the Welsh Conservative Party said his party was "open" to the name change, but pointed out that the sound of the word "MWP" is very similar to the word "muppet".
In this case, the Welsh letter "w" is pronounced similarly to the letter "u" in the English dialect of Yorkshire.
The committee working within the assembly, which is currently working on a bill changing the name, took the following position: "Naturally, the final decision on the future title of the assembly members will be their own."
The Government of Wales Act 2017 gave the Welsh National Assembly the power to change its name.
In June, the committee published the results of a public consultation on the proposal.
In addition, the committee supported the proposal to change the title of members of the assembly to "Member of the Welsh Parliament", or WMP in English, although this abbreviation "MWP" enjoyed the greatest popularity among the public.
The difficulty of reaching a consensus is a nuisance for Elin Jones, the president of the assembly, who should present the bill in the coming weeks.
The reform bill will also take into account other changes in the way the assembly works, including the rules for recalling members and the structure of the committee system.
Members of the National Assembly will be able to vote on their future title when discussing the bill.
