Shark injures 13-year-old diver in search of lobsters in California
Authorities reported that last Saturday a shark attacked and injured a 13-year-old diver in search of lobsters in California. The incident occurred on the first day of the lobster season.
The attack occurred just before 7 a.m. near Beacon's Beach in the U.S. city of Encinitas.
Chad Hammel reported to KSWB-TV in San Diego that on Saturday morning he was diving with friends for about half an hour when he heard a cry for help. Immediately with a group of friends they swam up to the boy to help pull him out of the water.
Hammel said that at first he thought the boy was excited about catching the lobster, but he soon realized that the child was screaming, “I’ve been bitten!
I was bitten!”
Upon reaching the scene, Chad Hammel noticed that the boy had completely torn skin in the clavicle area.
“I started yelling at everyone to run away from the water: ‘There’s a shark in the water!’” Hammel said.
The boy was transported by helicopter to the Children's Council Hospital in San Diego. His condition was described as critical.
The species of shark responsible for the attack remains unknown.
During a press conference, rescuer Captain Larry Giles said that the fish had been spotted several weeks earlier, but it was considered not to belong to the species of dangerous sharks.
Larry Giles added that the victim suffered severe upper torso injuries.
For the purpose of the investigation and for safety reasons, the authorities closed the entrance to the beach from Ponto Beach in Casablanca to Swami Beach in Ecinitas for 48 hours.
More than 135 species of sharks live in the area, although most are not considered to be dangerous.
Sainsbury’s is planning to expand into the UK cosmetics market.
The Sainsbury's chain is throwing the gauntlet at stores such as Boots, Superdrug and Debenhams, bringing to their supermarkets cosmetic departments that allude in style to department stores, as well as specially trained retailers.
As part of a significant investment in the UK beauty market - which is worth 2.8 billion pounds and is constantly growing despite declines in the fashion and household goods industry - 11 stores belonging to the network will have larger shelves with cosmetic products. If the initiative succeeds next year, the activities will be extended to further points.
The turn to the cosmetics industry results from the search for ways to manage the space previously occupied by televisions, microwaves and household items.
According to Sainsbury’s, the chain will double the number of cosmetic products and will offer up to 3,000 items. For the first time, products from brands such as Revlon, Essie, Tweezerman or Dr. PawPaw will appear in the assortment.
L’Oreal, Maybelline and Burt’s Bees will also get more space and separate areas similar to those known from Boots stores.
In addition, the supermarket chain plans to refresh its range of Boutique makeup products. From now on, most items will be vegan-friendly, which is increasingly demanded by younger customers.
In addition, Fragrance Shop will create test points at two Sainsbury’s supermarkets, the first one opened last week in Croydon, south London, and the second one will be in Selly Oak, Birmingham, later in the year.
The prevalence of online sales and daily purchases of small quantities of food in local shops means that supermarkets need to encourage customers to visit more.
Mike Coupe, president of Sainsbury's, said the outlets will increasingly resemble department stores as the chain tries to fight discount stores like Aldi or Lidl by offering more non-food services and products.
Sainsbury's has placed Argos points in hundreds of stores and introduced a number of Habitat points since the acquisition of both companies two years ago. According to the company, this contributes to increasing food sales and increasing the profitability of the investment.
The previous attempt to reorganize the departments with cosmetics and pharmaceuticals ended in failure.
At the beginning of the 21st century, Sainsbury's set up a joint venture with Boots as a trial venture. However, the cooperation was terminated following a conflict over the distribution of revenues from pharmacies operating in supermarkets.
Sainsbury’s is launching a new strategy following the sale of 281 pharmacies to Celesio, the owner of Lloyds Pharmacy, for an amount of ?125 million three years ago.
According to reports, Lloyds will contribute to the plan by bringing an expanded range of luxury skincare brands, including La Roche-Posay and Vichy, to the chain’s four stores.
Paul Mills-Hicks, Sainsbury’s Commercial Director, said: “We’ve transformed the look and feel of our cosmetics departments to improve the customer experience.
We have invested in special training for co-workers so that they can help consumers while shopping.
Our brands are able to meet all needs, and the friendly environment and convenient locations allow us to attract the attention of customers looking for cosmetic products, as well as question the ways of shopping so far.”
