Macedonians vote in referendum to change country's name
On Sunday, the Macedonians voted in a referendum on changing the name of their country to the Republic of North Macedonia. This movement would allow to resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece, which blocks the country's efforts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, where the historical land of Macedonia is located, maintains that the name of the northern neighbor is a claim to its territory. Therefore, it vetoed the country's accession to the EU and NATO.
In June, the governments of the two countries reached an agreement on naming, but nationalists say the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority living in Macedonia.
President Orge Ivanov said he would not take part in the vote. The campaign encouraging the boycott raised doubts as to whether the turnout would reach the minimum level of 50% required to make the referendum binding.
The referendum asked the following question: “Do you support joining NATO and the EU in the wake of the agreement with Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is worth paying the price for the possibility of joining Macedonia - one of the countries created after the fall of Yugoslavia - to such organizations as the European Union or NATO.
“I voted for the future of my country so that the young people of Macedonia can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union. EU membership will provide us all with greater security,” said 79-year-old Oleifera Georgijewska from Skopje.
Although the referendum is not legally binding, a sufficient number of parliamentarians have declared that they will respect the results of the vote.
The change of name requires the support of two-thirds of the members of parliament.
The state election commission reported that no unusual events had been reported by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout at that time was only 16% compared to 34% in the last parliamentary election of 2016, when 66% of eligible voters voted.
“I voted because of my children. Our place is in Europe,” said 62-year-old Oosze Tanewski, a voter from Skopje.
On 30 September 2018, in the city of Strumica in Macedonia, Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Duszko voted in a referendum on changing the country's name to open the way to NATO and European Union membership.
In front of the parliament building in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kawardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of tents spread out by people boycotting the referendum.
“We support NATO and EU membership, but we want to join these organizations with our heads held high, not the back door,” Kawardarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don’t want us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries like China or Russia and become part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring the necessary investment to Macedonia, where the unemployment rate is more than 20%.
"I believe that the vast majority will support the name change in the referendum, because 80% of citizens support the European Union and NATO," Zaev said after the vote.
He said that a “yes” vote was a “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian public research institute, 30 to 43% of voters declared their willingness to participate in the referendum. This is less than the required turnout.
According to another poll conducted by the Macedonian TV channel Telma TV, 57% of respondents plan to vote in Sunday’s referendum.
70% of respondents said they would support the name change.
For a vote to be successful, the turnout must be 50% + 1 vote.
The defeat in the referendum would be the first major blow to the pro-Western government’s policy since taking power last May.
