‘The sea belongs to us’: Bolivia, deprived of access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen its path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol around the naval base in La Paz.
Blue flags are flying from public buildings.
In the naval ports from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: “The sea is ours by law.
It is our duty to recover it.”
In the uninhabited sea of Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in the bloody conflict over the resources of the 19th century is still alive.
These hopes are perhaps the highest in decades, and Bolivia is awaiting a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1 after a five-year trial.
“Bolivia’s actions are gaining momentum. The residents are unanimous, optimistic and counting on a favorable verdict,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch a meeting of the International Court of Justice together. They hope that the organization based in The Hague will recognize Bolivia's claim and, after decades of fruitless talks, Chile will have to enter into negotiations to grant the state independent access to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic Bolivian president who will face a controversial re-election battle next year, also has hope in Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he vowed at the end of August.
However, some analysts say that the chances of a favorable ruling for Bolivia are small and that even a favorable decision would not change much.
The United Nations body based in The Hague does not have the authority to grant Bolivia the territory of Chile. He also warned that it would not affect the arrangements for possible talks.
According to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law, the decision of the International Court of Justice will be issued six months after the final arguments are presented. Such a short time shows that the case “was not complicated”.
Unfortunately for Bolivia, the last four years may have distanced the country from its goal.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Paz Zárate said.
Morales's relentless rhetoric deprived the Chileans of any vestige of goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but it will be very difficult in the face of the situation.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, the former president and Bolivian representative in The Hague, disagreed with the opinion that the court's decision-making process was extremely fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “a unique opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile” and the opportunity to “end a 139-year period of mutually beneficial disputes,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, used the issue of access to the sea as part of a political game.
