John Edward: language skills necessary for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their academic achievements - in 2018 they were able to boast another excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools with more than 30,000 students across Scotland strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another man in a language he understands, then it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages rank first in league rankings, with the highest pass rates in the case of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students scored higher on A in Mandarin, and 72 percent of learners of German, 69 percent of learners of French, and 63 percent of learners of Spanish also scored on A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as elective subjects, is conducted in the same scope as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) as part of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of job vacancies were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people to start their professional careers.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring language skills.
Lifelong skills, such as learning a second language, will give you a huge advantage in the future, regardless of your career path.
The possibility of direct communication with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language whose percentage of speakers was double-digit, i.e. 15%.
This is why investing in language learning is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught.
Many schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered the most important for the UK in the perspective of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of the child, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by teaching staff specialized in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed - whatever the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a large choice, variety and level.
It's the right thing to do.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
