North Korea says 'definitive no' to unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's foreign minister said Saturday during a speech at the United Nations that the failure to lift sanctions only exacerbates North Korea's lack of confidence in the United States and there is no way the country will unilaterally give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant measures of goodwill” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site of nuclear tests, and committing to non-proliferation and nuclear technology.
“But we don’t see any specific response from the US,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security, and in such circumstances there will be no unilateral disarmament of North Korea.”
While Ri echoed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's reluctance to a "gradual" approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual action, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization, as it has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent President of the United States and the leader of North Korea held on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised guarantees of North Korea’s security.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (1950-1953), but the U.S. delegation announced that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States is insisting on ‘denuclearization first’ and is increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the signing of a ‘declaration to end the war,’” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who behave towards us in an ignorant way.
The problem, however, is that the lack of lifting of sanctions deepens our mistrust."
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which the U.S. leader spoke about earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, after which he added: “If South Korea had been a party to the denuclearization issue and not the United States, then there would have been no such impasse on the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.”
The tone of Ri’s speech was completely different compared to last year when he said at the UN General Assembly that the targeting of North Korea’s missiles on U.S. territory is inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim Jong Un a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year, at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but also said much work needed to be done, and also stated that until North Korea is stripped of its nuclear weapons, sanctions will not be lifted.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not set a time frame for it, saying, "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue and be continuous until full, final and verified denuclearization is established.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly forum and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month in preparation for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit cannot be called a success.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that progress had been made, and within hours North Korea condemned him for "making gangster demands."
North Korea pledged this month at a meeting with Moon Jae-in that it would dismantle the missile test site and nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim Jong Un told him that the “appropriate measures” he cared about were the security guarantees Trump had pledged to provide in Singapore and taking steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course on adequately long rest
A new course at Harvard University this year provided all students with more sleep to combat the growing macho culture of “all-night caffeine-powered students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired to give a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
“After the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only told this now that I’m in my final year of college?’
She stated that no one ever told her about the meaning of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
During the course, which was held for the first time this year, it is explained to students how good sleep habits help to achieve good results in science and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, said the course was decided to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation within a week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive assignments.
One section includes a picture of a dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercises, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not result in an immediate change in student behavior.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as everyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking," added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “all-night learning” continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means a growing problem of sleep deprivation.
Ensuring enough good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even avoid weight gain because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheisler develop the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of a course for the entire campus.
The next step, according to him, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving on to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm to remind them when to go to sleep and when to get up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic device screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to trouble falling asleep.
