In one woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize hostile cells, ovarian cancer atrophy was observed for more than 18 months.
The method involves separating the immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can “perceive” a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then re-injecting the patient with these cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that this vaccine is prognosticating very well.”
HER2 “promotes the growth of several types of cancer,” including breast, ovarian, lung, and colon cancer, Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to locate cancer cells worked in the treatment of some type of leukemia.
