China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected, according to health workers in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases were sexually transmitted, which means a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people thus infected with HIV has been almost completely reduced, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, year-on-year, the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Given the country’s conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease are due to insufficient protection when having sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to HIV drugs as part of efforts to combat the problem.
