A unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it completely depends on the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide the resources, processes and relevant skills to help make the Solid platform available to all people.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers employed on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world were able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team aren’t talking to “Facebook and Google about whether to make a total change that will turn all their business models upside down overnight.
“I’m not asking for permission.”
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform."
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been heavily involved in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely excited to think about the next era in network development,” added Berners-Lee.
Bernard Vann: decoration of the clergyman with the Victoria Cross during the First World War
The memory of the only clergyman of the Church of England, who during the First World War was awarded the Victoria Cross, was celebrated 100 years later in his hometown.
Lieutenant-Colonel Bernard Vann was decorated on 29 September 1918 for advancing on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had been awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said the unveiling of the stone exactly on the centenary of his grandfather's decoration was "of an exceptionally symbolic nature."
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lt. Col. Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal “in very thick fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns.”
He then rushed to the line of fire and, with "the greatest courage" led her forward, then single-handedly launched an attack on the field guns station, incapacitating three of them.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I could never handle, but at the same time something humble.”
Together with his brother, Dr. James Vann, he laid a wreath after the end of the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honoured to be able to take part in the parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is manifested in the support he receives from many people".
