His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father didn't accept that he was dying, and one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets to the 2012 London Olympics - he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You won’t be with us to be in the front row, Dad,’” he said.
“I held his hand when he stopped breathing. It was only when he stopped breathing and died that I understood that he was not invincible,” he said.
The following year Daley took part in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I knew this was what I had dreamed of all my life - jumping into the water in front of a crowd of people at the Olympics - it was the best feeling possible," he said.
It also inspired him to choose his first song, Heather Small's Proud, which accompanied him in his preparations for the Olympic Games and which continues to give him goosebumps.
