New German warship delayed again
The German Navy’s newest frigate should be commissioned in 2014 to replace aging Cold War warships, but it won’t be until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the “Rheinland-Pfalz”, the main ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate, was postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing the words of a military spokesman.
The ship should be added to the Navy in 2014, but due to the problems that arose after the delivery, it was necessary to introduce changes to this ambitious project.
Four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
Of course, they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as technological solutions that prevent detection, ensuring, among others, the reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic traces.
Other important features include longer periods between maintenances - it should be possible to operate new frigates for up to two years away from home ports.
The constant delays mean, however, that these modern warships, which are supposed to enable Germany to respond to situations abroad, will be obsolete by the time the service begins, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned the ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind the return, but German media reported a number of key "software and hardware flaws" that made the ship useless in a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships are to be manned by a crew of about 120 sailors, which is half as many as the older Bremen-class frigates.
It also found the ship to be far too heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to carry out future upgrades.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as the German-built ships of the same class during World War II.
In addition to faulty equipment, the cost of the entire project - including crew training - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering EUR 3.1 billion (USD 3.6 billion), while the initial cost was EUR 2.2 billion.
The problems with the commissioning of the new frigates are of particular importance in the light of recent warnings that the strength of the German naval fleet is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, admitted that the navy was "running out of ships capable of use".
He also said that the problem has increased over time due to the decommissioning of old vessels without providing replacement vessels.
He also expressed his displeasure that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could be included in the navy.
National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
The new research, conducted at the Highlands estate in Scotland, aims to show how bats use the landscape to acquire food.
The findings are expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future efforts to protect them.
The research, led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will involve common and small dwarfs, as well as long-eared brown bats and bats from the red nocturnal family at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
In key locations around the property, special recorders will be deployed to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct fieldwork using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings is aimed at determining the frequency of signals sent by bats and the behavior of individual species.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their landscape-scale behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect perches and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly adhesives and some chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to the nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complex echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles in their path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly carry out tests, inspections of the perch, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organisation even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the grounds of the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the manager of the estate, says that it is an ideal territory for bats.
“Threeve has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns when it comes to bats. The work we do here and in other estates will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
It highlights the importance of checking for bats before undertaking maintenance work on the estates, as the inadvertent destruction of one perch can kill up to 400 females and young, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected - killing them, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their perch is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish Bat Conservation Trust officer, encouraged the public to provide assistance.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species we don’t even know how their populations fare.”
