All the conditions have already been met for refugees who had to leave the country because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods to return to the country voluntarily.
More than 5.5 million people have left Syria since the war began in 2011.
Another six million people who still live there are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to help rebuild the destroyed country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid offered by the countries that sponsored the rebellion.
Europe to seal victory at Ryder Cup in Paris
The Europe team won the 2018 Ryder Cup, defeating the US team with a score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National in the suburbs of Paris.
On European soil, the United States lost for the sixth time in a row and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the trophy when, under the leadership of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, it scored 14.5 points that were needed to defeat the US.
The American star, Phil Mickelson, who did not do well for most of the tournament, hit the ball from the stand straight into the water at the 16th hole of PAR3, thus giving the match to Francesca Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone through all the rounds and became one of four players who, since 1979, when this tournament was first held in the current format, managed to score 5-0-0.
American Jordan Spieth was eliminated 5&4 by the lowest ranked player from Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, who holds the top position in the world rankings, lost two holes before the last hole against Englishman Ian Poulter, for whom it may have been the last Ryder Cup tournament.
The European with the most wins in the Ryder Cup was Sergio Garcia, who has already taken part in eight such tournaments and scored 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t help myself.
It's been a tough year.
I am very grateful to Thomas for believing in me and choosing me.
I am so happy to have the cup back.
It’s a success for the whole team and I’m happy to be able to help,” Garcia said after the team’s victory in Europe.
He passes the baton to his compatriot, John Rahm, who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods in a singles game on Sunday, with a score of 2&1.
“I feel incredibly proud to have won against Tiger Woods. I grew up watching him play,” Rahm, 23, said.
Woods lost all his matches in France and now has a 13-21-3 result in the Ryder Cup.
This is an unprecedented statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who won 14 major titles and was inferior only to Jack Nicklaus.
The United States team had trouble finding treadmills all weekend, except for Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played at a really high level throughout the tournament.
After a disappointing performance by the American line-up, his captain, Jim Furyk, said, "I'm proud of the guys, they fought.
At some point this morning, we pressed some Europeans.
We pulled out.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players played really well.
Together with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Committee, we will find a way to move forward.
I love these 12 guys and am proud to be their captain.
I am full of admiration for my opponents.
They played much better than us.”
Flowering Information - Plankton Density Declines in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decline in plankton density in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of motley bloom has been reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It stretches for about 209 kilometres of coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
Blossoms can be encountered about 16 kilometres off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
The bloom has also been observed in Pasco County.
Last week saw average levels of plankton off the coast and in the waters of Pinellas County, low to medium off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high off the coast and in the waters of Sarasota County, natural to medium in Charlotte County, natural to high off the coast and in the waters of Lee County, and low in Collier County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation are still reported.
Last week, however, they were not recorded in northwestern Florida.
